  ECONOMICS
============================================================

Concept:    Compound Interest
Category:   Finance
Definition: Interest calculated on initial principal and accumulated interest
Formula:    A = P(1 + r/n)^(nt)
Economist:  Various
Example:    Einstein allegedly called it the 8th wonder of the world

Concept:    Central Bank
Category:   Macroeconomics
Definition: Government institution managing currency, money supply, interest rates
Formula:    Taylor Rule for interest rates
Economist:  John Taylor
Example:    US Federal Reserve raised rates to 5.25% in 2023 to fight inflation

Concept:    Monetarism
Category:   Macroeconomics
Definition: Inflation caused primarily by excessive money supply growth
Formula:    MV = PQ
Economist:  Milton Friedman
Example:    Fed raising interest rates to control money supply and inflation

============================================================
  QUESTION & ANSWER PAIRS
============================================================

Q1: What is metabolism?
A1: Metabolism is all chemical reactions in an organism
     that maintain life: catabolism (breaking molecules for
     energy) and anabolism (building complex molecules from
     simple ones).

Q2: What is the Big Bang?
A2: The Big Bang theory states the universe began from an
     extremely hot, dense point approximately 13.8 billion
     years ago and has been expanding ever since.

Q3: What is photosynthesis?
A3: Photosynthesis converts sunlight, CO2, and water into
     glucose and oxygen: 6CO2 + 6H2O + light → C6H12O6 +
     6O2. It occurs in plant chloroplasts.

Q4: What is a programming language?
A4: A programming language is a formal set of instructions
     for computers. High-level languages (Python, Java) are
     human-readable; low-level (Assembly) are closer to
     machine code.

Q5: What is machine learning?
A5: Machine learning enables systems to learn from
     experience without being explicitly programmed, using
     data to improve performance automatically.

============================================================
  PHILOSOPHY
============================================================

Concept:      Stoicism
Branch:       Ethics
Definition:   Focus only on what is in your control; accept all else with equanimity
Philosopher:  Marcus Aurelius/Epictetus
Example:      Illness is not in your control; your response to it is

Concept:      Categorical Imperative
Branch:       Ethics
Definition:   Act only on principles you could will to be universal laws
Philosopher:  Immanuel Kant
Example:      Don't lie; if universal lying existed, language would break down

Concept:      Virtue Ethics
Branch:       Ethics
Definition:   Ethics is about developing virtuous character traits
Philosopher:  Aristotle
Example:      A courageous person acts courageously habitually; ethics is becoming good

